Step 3 - Understand the data distribution

Create the following visualizations:

  • Histograms for each of the variables
  • Boxplot for Ozone, and boxplots for different wind values (round wind to get a good number of “buckets”)

HINT: you can create one graph with Ozone as X-axis and Wind as Y-axis. Also, you can create two graphs (one with Ozone values on the Y-axis, and another one with Y-axis value is rounded value of Wind). In this case, you need to create a fake grouping variable (x = factor(0)).

# Write your code below.
ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Ozone)) +
  geom_histogram()

ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Solar.R)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Wind)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Temp)) +

ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = as.numeric(Ozone), y = round(Wind, 1), group = Ozone)) +

Step 4 - Explore how the data changes over time

First, create the appropriate dates (this data was from 1973). Then create line charts for Ozone, Temp, Wind and Solar.R (one line chart for each, and then one chart with 4 lines, each variable having a different color).

HINT:

  1. Combine (use paste() function) 1973 with the Month and Day columns, using “/” in between
  2. Use as.Date() function to transform the value to “Date” format and create a Date column to record this value. Use ?as.Date to find example use of this function.

Note that for the chart with 4 lines, you need to think about how to effectively use the y-axis.

HINT: You need to “melt” the columns so that it becomes “long” format. You can either use the melt() function or use the gather() from the “tidyr” package for the process. Also, compared to other values, the Wind values are too small, so they are close to the x-axis. You need to multiply Wind by 10 to address this problem.

The correct result should look like this: 

# Write your code below.
# create a list of dates consisted with 1973/m/d format and add to the finshed_air dataset
finished_air$Date <- paste("1973", finished_air$Month, finished_air$Day, sep = "/")
# Transform chr values into date values
finished_air$Date <- as.Date(finished_air$Date, "%Y/%m/%d")
# We can remove Day and Month columns from the dataset now
finished_air <- finished_air[,-5:-6]
# Line charts for `Ozone`, `Temp`, `Wind` and `Solar.R` 
ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Date, y = Ozone)) +
  geom_line()

ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Date, y = Temp)) +
  geom_line() 

ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Date, y = Wind)) +
  geom_line() 

ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Date, y = Solar.R)) +
  geom_line() 

# melt
melted_air <- melt(finished_air, id = "Date")
ggplot(melted_air, aes(x = Date, y = value, color = variable)) +
  geom_line()

Step 5: Look at all the data via a heatmap

Create a heatmap, with each day (using dates) along the x-axis and Ozone, Temp, Wind and Solar.r along the y-axis.

Note that you need to figure out how to show the relative change equally across all the variables.

HINTS: - You may find this post helpful: - https://learnr.wordpress.com/2010/01/26/ggplot2-quick-heatmap-plotting/ - Melt the original table to make a long format before visualization using geom_tile()

Remember, your programming skills will improve as much as you struggle and put effort in them.

The correct result should look like this: 

# Write your code below.
ggplot(melted_air, aes(x = Date, y = variable, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile() + scale_fill_gradient(low="white", high="blue")

Step 6: Look at all the data via a scatter chart

Create a scatter chart, with: - the x-axis representing the Wind - the y-axis representing the Temp - the size of each dot representing the Ozone - the color representing Solar.R

# Write your code below.
ggplot(finished_air, aes(x = Wind, y = Temp)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = Ozone, color = Solar.R)) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "lightblue", high = "darkblue")

Step 7: Final analysis

You MUST answer to these questions in your compiled file.

Do you see any patterns after exploring the data?

The histogram shows that more recordings of Ozone levels are low (0~50 range) while recorded solar levels are mostly higher than median. For wind, the most frequently recorded values are approximately around 6 to 12. For temperature, the 70 to 90 seems to be most recorded so we can assume the location the recordings took place is a warm climate. The boxplot reflects on the Ozone value’s affect on Wind values. The chart shows that wind is generally recorded to be harsher as Ozone levels are lower. The line charts conveys that Solar values has the most dynamic changes over time, next is Ozone, then temperature, then wind. It is difficult to see any patterns within the line charts. In the heatmap, it is clear that the Ozone values are higher when the Temp and Solar values are higher meaning the Ozone is impacted by temperature and sun. On the other hand, there is little pattern that can be observed with the Wind variable. The scatter plot also shows that temperature is higher when Solar is higher. On the other hand, wind is lower when both of those variables tend to score high.

What was the most useful visualization?

I think that each visualization conveyed something, while the heatmap, the boxplot and the scatterplot contained particularly interesting patterns. If I were to comment on which of these were least useful, it would be the histograms and maybe even all of the line charts since there is little to no patterns that can be recognized through the human eye.
